1.Working with HTML elements
--> Text-level elements in HTML

Text-level elements (also called inline elements) are used inside text to style or give meaning to words, phrases, or small parts of content.
They do not start on a new line and only take as much space as needed.

‚≠ê Common Text-Level Elements
1.<a> -Anchor Tag - Marks content that acts as hyperlink
       eg., <a href="URL">Link Text</a>
	    <a href="tel:9876543210">Call Now</a>
	    <a href="mailto:example@gmail.com">Send Email</a>

2.<b> -> Bold text - Makes text bold (no extra importance).
	eg., <p>This is <b>bold</b> text</p>

3.<strong> -> Important text - Shows strong importance (also bold by default).
	eg., <p>This is <strong>important</strong> text</p>

4.<i> -> Italic text - Used for alternate voice or style.
	eg., <p>This is <i>italic</i> text</p>

5.<em> -> Emphasized text - Adds emphasis (usually italic).
	eg., <p>This is <em>emphasized</em> text</p>

6.<u> -> Underlined text
	eg., <p>This is <u>underlined</u> text</p>

7.<mark> -> Highlighted text
	eg., <p>This is <mark>highlighted</mark> text</p>

8.<small> -> Smaller text
	eg., <p>This is <small>small text</small></p>

9.<sup> -> Superscript - Used for powers, references.
	eg., <p>10<sup>2</sup></p>

10.<sub> -> Subscript - Used in chemical formulas.
	eg., <p>H<sub>2</sub>O</p>

11.<code> -> Code text - Shows programming code.
	eg., <p>Use <code>printf()</code> function</p>

12.<span> -> Generic inline container - Used for styling with CSS.
	eg., <p>This is <span style="color:red;">red</span> text</p>

#Grouping Elements in HTML
Grouping elements are used to group multiple HTML elements together so we can:
1.Structure the webpage
2.Apply CSS styles easily
3.Manage layout and content clearly

They do not add meaning by themselves, they just group content.
1.<blockquote> - Adds quotation marks and indentation to content
2.<div> - Contains a generic grouping of elements within the document
3.<hr> - Adds a line break by adding horizontal line between content
4.<ol> - Contains ordered list of items
5.<ul> - Contains unordered list of items
6.<li> - Contains a single item from a list
7.<nav> - Marks a list of hypertext or navigation links

üîë Main Grouping Elements
1. <div> -> Block-level grouping element
Used to group large sections of content.

<div>
  <h2>Login</h2>
  <p>Enter your details</p>
</div>


‚úî Block-level
‚úî Starts on a new line
‚úî Most commonly used

2. <span> -> Inline grouping element

Used to group small parts of text.

<p>This is <span style="color:red;">important</span> text</p>


‚úî Inline
‚úî Does not start new line
‚úî Used inside text

**Difference Between <div> and <span>
Feature		<div>			<span>
Type		Block-level		Inline
New line	Yes			No
Usage		Layout / sections	Text styling
Content		Large blocks		Small text

## Semantic Grouping Elements (HTML5)
These also group content, but with meaning.

<header> -> Top section

<nav> -> Navigation links

<section> -> Related content

<article> -> Independent content

<aside> -> Side content

<footer> -> Bottom section

<main> -> Main content

Example:

<section>
  <h2>About Us</h2>
  <p>We build web apps</p>
</section>

